## 2. LITERATURE REVIEW

### 2.1 Identity Management in Educational Institutions
Traditional identity management in educational institutions has relied on physical tokens such as ID cards, passwords, and manual verification processes. However, these methods present several security and operational challenges. According to Smith et al. (2021), identity fraud rates in Nigerian universities range from 15% to 30%, indicating significant vulnerabilities in conventional systems.

### 2.2 Biometric Technologies in Academic Settings
Biometric systems have demonstrated superior security capabilities compared to traditional methods. Research by Johnson and Williams (2020) indicates that biometric systems reduce unauthorized access by up to 95% while improving verification accuracy to over 99%.

### 2.3 Facial Recognition Technology
Facial recognition technology has emerged as a particularly suitable biometric modality for educational environments due to its non-intrusive nature and widespread hardware availability. The technology analyzes distinctive facial features using advanced algorithms to create unique identity templates.

### 2.4 QR Code Integration
QR (Quick Response) codes provide an effective bridge between digital and physical verification processes. Their high data capacity and scannability with standard devices make them ideal for verification systems (Lee et al., 2019).

